msgid "Finds `my-pipeline` with status `Running`"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:819
msgid ""
"Marks it as `Failed { error: \"coordinator restarted\" }`, increments "
"generation"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:820
msgid ""
"Logs: `INFO recovering stale dataflow <uuid> (\"my-pipeline\") -> marking as "
"Failed`"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:821
msgid "`dora list` now shows `my-pipeline` with its final status and timestamps"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:822
msgid ""
"Daemons detect the coordinator disconnect independently and stop their nodes"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:823
msgid "User can start a fresh dataflow -- the coordinator is fully operational"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:825
msgid ""
"The key benefit: the coordinator retains a complete history of dataflow "
"lifecycle events across restarts. Without `--store redb`, all state would be "
"lost and the operator would have no record of what was running before the "
"crash."
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:827
msgid "7. Periodic Batch Job with Always-Restart"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:829
msgid ""
"A node that processes batches and exits when done. It should restart to "
"process the next batch."
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:833
msgid "batch-processor"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:834
msgid "./target/debug/batch-proc"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:835
msgid "always        # restart even on clean exit\n    max_restarts"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:837
msgid "# wait 10s between batches\n    max_restart_delay"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:838
msgid "# no exponential growth\n    inputs"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:840
msgid "trigger"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:840
msgid "dora/timer/millis/1  # immediate first trigger\n    outputs"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:842
msgid "batch-result"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:845
msgid ""
"The node processes one batch, exits with code 0, waits 10s, then restarts to "
"process the next. The `always` policy ensures restarts even on success. "
"Setting `restart_delay == max_restart_delay` gives a constant delay."
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:851
msgid ""
"**Start with `on-failure`**. Use `always` only for nodes that are expected "
"to exit and restart (e.g., periodic batch jobs)."
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:853
msgid ""
"**Set `max_restarts`**. Unlimited restarts can mask bugs. Start with 3-5 and "
"increase if needed. Use `max_restarts: 0` only for nodes where crashes are "
"expected and unavoidable (hardware drivers, external API clients)."
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:855
msgid ""
"**Use `restart_window`**. Prevents permanent restart loops. A window of "
"60-300 seconds is typical. Without a window, a node that crashes at startup "
"will exhaust its restart budget immediately."
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:857
msgid ""
"**Tune `restart_delay`**. Start with 0.5-1.0 seconds. Too short causes "
"thrashing; too long delays recovery. Match the delay to your node's typical "
"startup time and the root cause of failures:"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:858
msgid "USB/hardware reconnection: 2-5s"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:859
msgid "Network service reconnection: 1-3s"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:860
msgid "OOM/transient bugs: 0.5-1.0s"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:862
msgid ""
"**Set `health_check_timeout` generously**. Should be at least 2-3x your "
"node's longest expected processing time. ML inference nodes may need 60s+. "
"If too short, healthy nodes get killed during normal processing."
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:864
msgid ""
"**Set `input_timeout` per input**. Not all inputs need the same timeout. Use "
"shorter timeouts for high-frequency inputs (IMU, camera) and longer timeouts "
"for slow/bursty sources (GPS, batch results). A good starting point is 3-5x "
"the expected publish interval."
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:866
msgid ""
"**Use `InputTracker` for critical paths**. When a node must keep running "
"even with degraded inputs, use `InputTracker` to fall back to cached data. "
"This is essential for sensor fusion, planning, and control nodes."
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:868
msgid ""
"**Use `--store redb` for production deployments**. The redb backend ensures "
"the coordinator retains dataflow history across crashes and restarts. The "
"in-memory default is fine for development but loses all state on exit. The "
"redb file is small (proportional to the number of dataflow records) and adds "
"negligible overhead."
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:870
msgid "**Combine features for defense in depth**:"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:871
msgid "`restart_policy` + `restart_delay` -> recover from node crashes"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:872
msgid "`health_check_timeout` -> recover from hung nodes"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:873
msgid "`input_timeout` -> detect stale upstream data"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:874
msgid "`InputTracker` -> graceful degradation in node code"
msgstr ""

#: src/operations/fault-tolerance.md:875
msgid "`--store redb` -> survive coordinator crashes"
msgstr ""

